<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Derivative</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Calculus/Derivative.nb" =
download=3D"Derivative.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images=
/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" alt=3D"DOWN=
LOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download <span class=3D"display-i display-=
n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</span></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The derivative of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Function.html"=
>function</a> represents an infinitesimal
change in the function with respect to one of its variables.
</p>
<p>
The "simple" derivative of a function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/images/equations/Derivative/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"f"> with respect to a variable <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/Derivative/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" styl=
e=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"x"> is denoted either <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"40" height=3D"22" alt=3D"=
f^'(x)"> or
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"33" height=
=3D"39" alt=3D" (df)/(dx), "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
often written in-line as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/Derivative/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"60" height=3D"21" alt=3D"df/dx=
">.
 When derivatives are taken with respect to time, they are often denoted us=
ing Newton's
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Overdot.html">overdot</a> notatio=
n for <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Fluxion.html">fluxions</a>,
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"59" height=
=3D"39" alt=3D" (dx)/(dt)=3Dx^.. "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn2" class=3D"eqnum">
(2)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
The "d-ism" of Leibniz's <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/Derivative/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"56" height=3D"21" alt=3D"df/dt=
"> eventually won the notation battle against the "dotage"
 of Newton's fluxion notation (P.&nbsp;Ion, pers. comm., Aug.&nbsp;18, 2006=
).
</p>
<p>
When a derivative is taken <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images=
/equations/Derivative/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 times, the notation <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equat=
ions/Derivative/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"50" height=3D"22" alt=3D"f^((n))(x=
)">
 or
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation3.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"36" height=
=3D"40" alt=3D" (d^nf)/(dx^n) "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn3" class=3D"eqnum">
(3)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
is used, with
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation4.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"46" height=
=3D"20" alt=3D" x^.,x^..,x^..., "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn4" class=3D"eqnum">
(4)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
etc., the corresponding <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Fluxion.ht=
ml">fluxion</a> notation.
</p>
<p>
When a function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
Derivative/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"81" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f(x,y,...)">
 depends on more than one variable, a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/PartialDerivative.html">partial derivative</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation5.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"118" height=
=3D"46" alt=3D" (partialf)/(partialx),(partial^2f)/(partialxpartialy), etc.=
 "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn5" class=3D"eqnum">
(5)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
can be used to specify the derivative with respect to one or more variables=
.
</p>
<p>
The derivative of a function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/imag=
es/equations/Derivative/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-h=
eight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f=
(x)"> with respect to the variable <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/equations/Derivative/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" =
alt=3D"x"> is defined as
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation6.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"196" height=
=3D"39" alt=3D" f^'(x)=3Dlim_(h-&gt;0)(f(x+h)-f(x))/h, "></td><td align=3D"=
right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn6" class=3D"eqnum">
(6)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
but may also be calculated more symmetrically as
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation7.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"224" height=
=3D"39" alt=3D" f^'(x)=3Dlim_(h-&gt;0)(f(x+h)-f(x-h))/(2h), "></td><td alig=
n=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn7" class=3D"eqnum">
(7)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
provided the derivative is known to exist.
</p>
<p>
It should be noted that the above definitions refer to "real" derivatives, =
i.e., derivatives which are restricted to directions along the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/RealAxis.html">real
 axis</a>. However, this restriction is artificial, and derivatives are mos=
t naturally
 defined in the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ComplexPlane.html"=
>complex plane</a>, where they are sometimes
 explicitly referred to as <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Complex=
Derivative.html">complex derivatives</a>.
 In order for complex derivatives to exist, the <i>same</i> result must be =
obtained
 for derivatives taken in any direction in the <a href=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/ComplexPlane.html">complex
 plane</a>. Somewhat surprisingly, almost all of the important functions in=
 mathematics
 satisfy this property, which is equivalent to saying that they satisfy the=
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Cauchy-RiemannEquations.html">Cau=
chy-Riemann
 equations</a>.
</p>
<p>
These considerations can lead to confusion for students because elementary =
calculus texts commonly consider only "real" derivatives, never alluding to=
 the
 existence of complex derivatives, variables, or functions. For example, te=
xtbook
 examples to the contrary, the "derivative" (read: <a href=3D"https://mathw=
orld.wolfram.com/ComplexDerivative.html">complex
 derivative</a>) <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/Derivative/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"63" height=3D"21" alt=3D"d|z|/dz">
 of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AbsoluteValue.html">absolu=
te value</a> function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/Derivative/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:=
100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=3D"|z|"> d=
oes not exist because at every point in the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wo=
lfram.com/ComplexPlane.html">complex
 plane</a>, the value of the derivative depends on the direction in which t=
he derivative
 is taken (so the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Cauchy-RiemannEq=
uations.html">Cauchy-Riemann equations</a>
 cannot and do not hold). However, the <i>real</i> derivative (i.e., restri=
cting the
 derivative to directions along the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/RealAxis.html">real axis</a>) <i>can</i>
 be defined for points other than <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/images/equations/Derivative/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D=
"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" al=
t=3D"x=3D0"> as
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Derivative/NumberedEquation8.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"198" height=
=3D"81" alt=3D" (d|x|)/(dx)=3D{-1   for x&lt;0; undefined   for x=3D0; 1   =
for x&gt;0. "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn8" class=3D"eqnum">
(8)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
As a result of the fact that computer algebra languages and programs such a=
s the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> gen=
erically deal
 with complex variables (i.e., the definition of derivative always means <i=
>complex</i>
 derivative), <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/De=
rivative/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"65" height=3D"21" alt=3D"d|x|/dx">
 correctly returns unevaluated by such software.
</p>
<p>
If the first derivative exists, the second derivative may be defined as
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
