td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn10" class=3D"eqnum">
(10)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
again provided the second derivative is known to exist.
</p>
<p>
Note that in order for the limit to exist, both <img src=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Derivative/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"53" he=
ight=3D"22" alt=3D"lim_(h-&gt;0^+)"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolf=
ram.com/images/equations/Derivative/Inline16.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" s=
tyle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"53" height=3D=
"22" alt=3D"lim_(h-&gt;0^-)"> must exist and be equal, so the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://mathworld.wolfram.com/Function.html">function</a>
 must be continuous. However, continuity is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/Necessary.html">necessary</a>
 but <i>not</i> <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Sufficient.html">s=
ufficient</a> condition for differentiability.
 Since some <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Discontinuous.html">di=
scontinuous</a> functions can be integrated,
 in a sense there are "more" functions which can be integrated than differe=
ntiated.
 In a letter to Stieltjes, Hermite wrote, "I recoil with dismay and horror =
at
 this lamentable plague of functions which do not have derivatives."
</p>
<p>
A three-dimensional generalization of the derivative to an arbitrary direct=
ion is known as the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DirectionalDer=
ivative.html">directional derivative</a>. In
 general, derivatives are mathematical objects which exist between smooth f=
unctions
 on manifolds. In this formalism, derivatives are usually assembled into "<=
a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TangentMap.html">tangent maps</a>."
</p>
<p>
Performing <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NumericalDifferentiatio=
n.html">numerical differentiation</a> is in many ways more difficult than <=
a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NumericalIntegration.html">numerica=
l
 integration</a>. This is because while <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/NumericalIntegration.html">numerical
 integration</a> requires only good continuity properties of the function b=
eing integrated,
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NumericalDifferentiation.html">nu=
merical differentiation</a> requires more
 complicated properties such as Lipschitz classes.
</p>
